    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Lead Assignment Rules (Article) ──────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Lead Assignment Rules",
            Slug = "assignment-rules-overview",
            Summary = "How to create priority-ordered rules that automatically route incoming leads to the right rep: Round Robin, Territory, Industry, and Account-Based kinds.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/assignment-rules"]""",
            Tags = """["admin","automations","leads","assignment","routing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Lead Assignment Rules\n\nAssignment rules decide which sales rep a new lead goes to, automatically, the moment the lead is created. Instead of someone hand-picking an owner for every lead, you set up a small list of rules once and the system does it for you. This page — Admin → Assignment Rules — is where those rules live.\n\n### How rules are applied\n\nRules run **in priority order**, lowest number first. The first **active** rule that fits the new lead wins, and that rule decides the owner. A rule that's switched off is skipped. Because the first match wins, the order matters: put your most specific rules (a particular region, a key account) at a lower priority number so they're checked before broad catch-all rules.\n\nThink of it as a waterfall: the lead drops down through the active rules, starting at the lowest priority number, and lands on the first one it fits.\n\n### Rule types\n\nEvery rule has a **type** that decides both which leads it fits and which rep it picks:\n\n- **Round Robin** — spreads leads evenly across a group of reps. You pick the reps who take part, and each new lead goes to the next rep in turn. Use this for a general intake queue where any qualified rep can take the lead.\n- **Territory** — matches leads by location. You list the states and/or ZIP codes the rule covers, and a lead with an address in that area goes to the rule's owner. Use this when reps own regions.\n- **Industry** — matches leads by their industry. You list the industries the rule covers. Use this when reps specialize by field, such as aerospace, medical, or automotive.\n- **Account-Based** — sends a lead to whoever already owns the company it belongs to, so every contact at that company lands with the same rep. This type needs no extra fields — the company link does the work.\n\n### Creating a rule\n\nClick **New Rule** to open the rule window. Every rule needs three things:\n\n1. **Name** — a label so you can recognize the rule in the list, such as \"West Coast Territory\" or \"Aerospace Specialists\".\n2. **Type** — pick one of the four types above. Picking a type shows the fields that type needs.\n3. **Priority** — the order number that decides when the rule is checked (lower = checked first). Two rules can share a number, but giving each its own keeps the order predictable.\n\nThen fill in the **fields for that type**:\n\n- Round Robin → the **reps** to rotate through.\n- Territory → the **states** and/or **ZIP codes** the region covers.\n- Industry → the **industries** the rule covers.\n- Account-Based → no extra fields; a note reminds you the company link does the work.\n\nClick **Save** to create the rule. New rules are active right away.\n\n### Editing, pausing, and deleting\n\n- **Edit** (the pencil, or clicking the row) reopens the rule window. While editing, an **Active** switch lets you pause a rule without deleting it — a paused rule is skipped but kept for later.\n- **Delete** (the trash icon) removes a rule after you confirm. Deleting the rule is permanent; leads already assigned don't change.\n\n### The advanced option\n\nBelow the type fields is a collapsible **Advanced** section. The fields above are the normal way to set up a rule, and most admins never need to open this section. It's a backup for rare cases the standard form doesn't cover yet, and when the regular fields are filled in they always take priority over anything here.\n\n### Who can use it\n\nAssignment rules are available to Admins and Managers. Creating and editing a rule needs the Admin or Manager role; deleting a rule needs Admin.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Assignment Rules Field Reference (QuickRef) ──────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Assignment Rules Field Reference",
            Slug = "assignment-rules-field-reference",
            Summary = "Reference for the Assignment Rules list columns, the rule window fields for each type, what each field means, and the rules for saving.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
